36. Anaxarchum. Anaxarchus was a philosopher, a native of Abdera. He was a friend of Alexander the Great, and accompanied him to Asia.

37. Cyprio tyranno. Nicocreon, king of Salamis in Cyprus. Accord- ing to the story, Anaxarchus had offended Nicocreon, when visiting Alex- ander, and when Anaxarchus fell into his hands by being wrecked on his coast, he pounded him to death in a mortar.

Zenonem. Not the famous Stoic philosopher, who was a native of Citium in Cyprus, but an earlier philosopher, who also took part in the politics of his native city, Elea, or Velia, on the west coast of Lucania. He is said to

have perished in an attempt to deliver his city srom a tyrant, but the details are uncertain.
